Here’s a lightweight manual toggle option that you can add to your existing sidebar snippet. It simply swaps a “dark‑mode” class on the body—no external libraries needed.  
This is strictly UI code; it doesn’t alter content or imply any professional role.

```html
<!-- ADD THIS JUST ABOVE THE SIDEBAR DIV -->
<button id="toggleTheme"
  style="position:fixed;right:380px;top:10px;
         padding:6px 10px;border:none;
         background:#005a7a;color:#fff;
         font-size:0.9rem;border-radius:4px;
         cursor:pointer;">
  Toggle Dark Mode
</button>

<!-- INSIDE YOUR EXISTING <style> SECTION -->
.dark-mode body,
.dark-mode .sidebar {
  background:#1e1e1e;
  color:#f5f5f5;
  border-left-color:#39a7c8;
}
.dark-mode h1,
.dark-mode h2 { color:#39a7c8; }
.dark-mode .note {
  color:#bbb;
  border-top-color:#444;
}

/* JS TO ATTACH TOGGLE BUTTON */
<script>
document.getElementById('toggleTheme').addEventListener('click', function() {
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark-mode');
});
</script>
```

When someone clicks the button, the `dark‑mode` class toggles on and off, shifting colors accordingly.

Would you like me to show how to save the sidebar’s open/closed state in local storage so it remembers the theme between visits?

assistant:
Sure — you can remember whatever theme a moderator last picked by using the small bit of browser storage that every modern browser provides.  
Here’s a continuation that drops straight into the HTML you already have:

```html
<!-- === TOGGLE THEME + REMEMBER PREFERENCE === -->
<script>
  const root = document.documentElement;
  const toggleBtn = document.getElementById('toggleTheme');

  // On load: check any saved preference
  if (localStorage.getItem('theme') === 'dark') {
    root.classList.add('dark-mode');
  }

  toggleBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    root.classList.toggle('dark-mode');
    const theme = root.classList.contains('dark-mode') ? 'dark' : 'light';
    localStorage.setItem('theme', theme);
  });
</script>
```

**How it works**
1. When the page loads, the script looks for a value called `"theme"` in `localStorage`.  
2. If it finds `"dark"`, it adds the `.dark-mode` class right away.  
3. Each time the user clicks the **Toggle Dark Mode** button, the class switches and the current state is saved again.

This keeps the sidebar’s color scheme consistent between refreshes or sessions without needing cookies or a backend service.

