Here’s a simple collapse/expand toggle that keeps your sidebar from taking up too much screen space while still being easy to reopen.  
This adds a second button and a few lines of CSS and JS—again, purely functional UI code.

```html
<!-- ==== COLLAPSE / EXPAND BUTTON ==== -->
<button id="collapseSidebar"
  style="position:fixed;right:10px;top:10px;
         padding:6px 10px;border:none;
         background:#39a7c8;color:#fff;
         font-size:0.9rem;border-radius:4px;
         cursor:pointer;">
  Hide Guide
</button>

<!-- ADD TO YOUR STYLE SECTION -->
.collapsed .sidebar {
  width: 0;
  padding: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
  border-left: none;
}
.collapsed #collapseSidebar {
  right: 10px;             /* stay visible */
  top: 10px;
}
.collapsed #toggleTheme {
  display: none;           /* optional: hide the theme button */
}

/* optional transition */
.sidebar { transition: width 0.3s ease, padding 0.3s ease; }

<!-- ADD TO YOUR JS SECTION BELOW THE THEME SCRIPT -->
<script>
  const collapseBtn = document.getElementById('collapseSidebar');
  collapseBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
    document.documentElement.classList.toggle('collapsed');
    const collapsed = document.documentElement.classList.contains('collapsed');
    collapseBtn.textContent = collapsed ? 'Show Guide' : 'Hide Guide';
    localStorage.setItem('sidebarState', collapsed ? 'collapsed' : 'expanded');
  });

  // Restore last state
  if (localStorage.getItem('sidebarState') === 'collapsed') {
    document.documentElement.classList.add('collapsed');
    collapseBtn.textContent = 'Show Guide';
  }
</script>
```

When **Hide Guide** is clicked, the sidebar slides away; clicking **Show Guide** brings it back.  
It also remembers the last state in `localStorage`, so the layout is the same on the next visit.

