Here are the few HTML updates you can drop in so your sidebar passes basic accessibility checks.  
They only add ARIA labels and focus semantics—no functional changes, and nothing clinical.

```html
<!-- WRAP SIDEBAR IN A NAV FOR CLEAR ROLE -->
<nav class="sidebar" aria-label="Empathic‑Support Quick Reference" role="complementary">

  <!-- Collapse / expand button -->
  <button id="collapseSidebar"
          aria-controls="sidebarContent"
          aria-expanded="true"
          style="position:fixed;right:10px;top:10px;
                 padding:6px 10px;border:none;
                 background:#39a7c8;color:#fff;
                 font-size:0.9rem;border-radius:4px;
                 cursor:pointer;">
    Hide Guide
  </button>

  <div id="sidebarContent" tabindex="-1">
     … existing content …
  </div>

</nav>
```

And then, in your JavaScript where you toggle the collapsed state:

```js
const collapseBtn = document.getElementById('collapseSidebar');
const sidebarContent = document.getElementById('sidebarContent');

collapseBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle('collapsed');
  const collapsed = document.documentElement.classList.contains('collapsed');
  collapseBtn.textContent = collapsed ? 'Show Guide' : 'Hide Guide';
  collapseBtn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', !collapsed);
  sidebarContent.focus(); // keep logical keyboard focus
  localStorage.setItem('sidebarState', collapsed ? 'collapsed' : 'expanded');
});
```

**What this does**
- Gives assistive tech a clear name for the region.  
- Keeps keyboard users aware whether the panel is open or closed.  
- Shifts focus correctly so navigation remains logical.

That finishes the accessibility loop so your guide scores well in automated audits.

