Here’s a small configuration file you can drop alongside that workflow so Lighthouse knows what to measure.  
It sticks to performance and accessibility—nothing clinical or user‑specific.

```json
{
  "ci": {
    "collect": {
      "staticDistDir": "./",
      "numberOfRuns": 3,
      "settings": {
        "onlyCategories": ["accessibility", "performance"],
        "emulatedFormFactor": "desktop",
        "throttlingMethod": "simulate"
      }
    },
    "assert": {
      "assertions": {
        "categories:accessibility": ["warn", { "minScore": 0.9 }],
        "categories:performance": ["warn", { "minScore": 0.9 }],
        "color-contrast": ["warn"],
        "aria-allowed-attr": ["warn"]
      }
    },
    "upload": {
      "target": "temporary-public-storage"
    }
  }
}
```

**Usage**
1. Save this as `.lighthouserc.json` in your repo root.  
2. The GitHub Action reads it automatically and enforces the same ≥ 90 score targets you’ve been using.  
3. Results appear as comments or checks on each pull request, so you catch layout or contrast regressions before merging.

